<chapter xml:id='chap-whats-new'
         xmlns='http://docbook.org/ns/docbook' version='5.0' xml:lang='en'
         xmlns:xsi='http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance'
         xsi:schemaLocation='http://docbook.org/ns/docbook
                             http://docbook.org/xml/5.0/xsd/docbook.xsd'
         xmlns:xlink='http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink'>
 <title>What's New in ${projectName}</title>

 <!-- Alternative for maintenance releases:
 <para>
  ${projectName} ${docTargetVersion} is a maintenance release.
  It does not introduce new features.
 </para>
 -->

 <itemizedlist>
  <para>
   ${projectName} ${docTargetVersion} fixes a number of issues,
   and provides the following additional features.
  </para>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} can now store session information
    in encrypted JSON Web Token (JWT) cookies on the user-agent (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-224"
     >OPENIG-224</link>,
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-278"
     >OPENIG-278</link>).
    By default, ${projectName} continues to back session information
    with HttpSession from the container where ${projectName} runs.
   </para>

   <para>
    With this change, you can specify the session storage
    at the global level, or in a particular route configuration.
    For details, see
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="reference#JwtSession"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
     >JwtSession</link>
    and
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="gateway-guide#keystore-for-jwt-encryption"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
     ><citetitle>Setting Up Keys For JWT Encryption</citetitle></link>.
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} now allows you to inline configuration objects (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-311"
    >OPENIG-311</link>),
    to omit "config" fields when all values are optional (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-300"
    >OPENIG-300</link>),
    to omit the "objects" field from the "heap"
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-380"
    >OPENIG-380</link>),
    and even to omit the "heap" when it is empty
    or would only contain a single handler (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-329"
    >OPENIG-329</link>).
   </para>

   <para>
    When you bring an object inline, you no longer need to specify the "name".
   </para>

   <para>
    For example,
    suppose your former <filename>config.json</filename> file looks like this:
   </para>

   <programlisting language="javascript">
{
    "heap": {
        "objects": [
            {
                "name": "Chain",
                "type": "Chain",
                "config": {
                    "filters": [
                        "ReplaceHostFilter"
                    ],
                    "handler": "Router"
                }
            },
            {
                "name": "ReplaceHostFilter",
                "type": "HeaderFilter",
                "config": {
                    "messageType": "REQUEST",
                    "remove": [
                        "host"
                    ],
                    "add": {
                        "host": [
                            "example.com"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            {
                "name": "Router",
                "type": "Router",
                "config": {}
            }
        ]
    },
    "handler": "Chain"
}
   </programlisting>

   <para>
    ${projectName} now lets you rewrite
    the <filename>config.json</filename> file like this:
   </para>

   <programlisting language="javascript">
{
    "handler": {
        "type": "Chain",
        "config": {
            "filters": [
                {
                    "type": "HeaderFilter",
                    "config": {
                        "messageType": "REQUEST",
                        "remove": [
                            "host"
                        ],
                        "add": {
                            "host": [
                                "example.com"
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                }
            ],
            "handler": {
                "type": "Router"
            }
        }
    }
}
   </programlisting>

   <para>
    Examples in the documentation now use streamlined configurations
    where it makes sense.
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <!-- Related issues: OPENIG-369, OPENIG-360 -->
   <para>
    ${projectName} now supports object decorators (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-340"
     >OPENIG-340</link>).
    Decorators allow you to define heap objects that decorate other objects,
    adding the new behavior that the decorator provides.
   </para>

   <itemizedlist>
    <para>
     ${projectName} provides the following decorators out of the box.
    </para>

    <listitem>
     <para>
      A CaptureDecorator that extends what the CaptureFilter could do
      to capture requests, responses, and exchange data on any decorated object
      (<link
       xlink:show="new"
       xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-299"
      >OPENIG-299</link>,
      <link
       xlink:show="new"
       xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-301"
      >OPENIG-301</link>)
     </para>
    </listitem>

    <listitem>
     <para>
      A TimerDecorator that records times to process the exchange
      through any decorated object (
      <link
       xlink:show="new"
       xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-352"
      >OPENIG-352</link>,
      <link
       xlink:show="new"
       xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-353"
      >OPENIG-353</link>)
     </para>
    </listitem>

    <listitem>
     <para>
      An AuditDecorator that allows you to audit operation
      for any decorated object.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </itemizedlist>

   <para>
    For detailed information about decorators,
    see the <citetitle>Reference</citetitle> on
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="reference#decorators-conf"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
     ><citetitle>Decorators</citetitle></link>.
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} now provides a publish-and-subscribe audit framework
    and a sample monitoring handler that returns basic statistics (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-359"
     >OPENIG-359</link>,
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-386"
     >OPENIG-386</link>).
    To learn more, start by reading the chapter about the
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="gateway-guide#chap-auditing"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
    ><citetitle>${projectName} Audit Framework</citetitle></link>.
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} script configurations can now include arguments (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-240"
    >OPENIG-240</link>).
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    The OAuth2ClientFilter and OAuth2ResourceServerFilter now cache data
    to avoid unnecessarily calls to the provider (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-350"
    >OPENIG-350</link>).
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    ${projectName} uses improved object names in log messages
    that make it easier to identify the source of the message (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-358"
    >OPENIG-358</link>,
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-371"
    >OPENIG-371</link>).
   </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
   <para>
    The ${projectName} Exchange now provides information about the client (
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="https://bugster.forgerock.org/jira/browse/OPENIG-333"
     >OPENIG-333</link>).
   </para>

   <para>
    For details see the <citetitle>Reference</citetitle> on
    <link
     xlink:show="new"
     xlink:href="reference#ClientInfo"
     xlink:role="http://docbook.org/xlink/role/olink"
     ><citetitle>ClientInfo</citetitle></link>.
   </para>
  </listitem>
 </itemizedlist>
 </chapter>
